Motivation and background

There exists many resources that document various aspects of entertainment, whether it be books, games, movies, or tv shows. One popular example of this is fandom.com, which claims to be hosted on over 385000 domains, with over 50000000 pages. However, there exist few studies of fandom's wikis, likely due to the lack of updated repositories. Hence, I intend to conduct a study on various aspects of Fandom's wiki repository.

Summary of Research Questions

  1. What are the correlations betweeen emotional weight of wiki text and the positivity/negativity of the same text?
  • Entertainment can induce a variety of emotions in individuals. These emotions are often dictated by a set of words that indicate an emotional weight. The overrall emotional weight of a body of text can hence be determined by the sum of emotional weights of every word. Hence, I would like to determine the positivity/negativity of Fandom wikis, based on the emotional weight of its text. I would also like to find if there exists correlations betweeen different emotions.
  1. Which external domains are commonly used for each genre of wiki?
  • Fandom wikis often reference external links in their contents. Certain genres of wikis may reference some domains more often. e.g. Music centered wikis may reference soundcloud more. Hence, I would like to find which external domains are commonly used for each genre of wiki
  1. How has the presence of movies on Fandom changed over time?
  • Fandom is also a hub for storing content on Movies. The evolution of digital entertainment has meant that Movies are attracting a far larger audience than before, and corrospondingly, a larger Fandom userbase. Hence, I would like to find how the presence of movies on Fandom has changed over time.

Dataset

Description of data and links

There exists no comprehensive and updated list of all fandom wikis. Hence, I have taken data from multiple sources to obtain the most comprehensive list possible

  1. https://community.fandom.com/wiki/Special:NewWikis
  • Fandom has many so called 'Special Pages', which allow users to query data on all fandom wikis. From the data obtained and implied by its name, I have concluded that Special:NewWikis indexes fandom wikis when they are created, although this has not been confirmed by Fandom. Parameters limit, language, and category can be passed to this endpoint. Significant data cleaning was done on the returned data, as there were many duplicate entries, and broken or invalid links. Wikis are also removed from this endpoint regularly, comparisons between 2 datasets taken from 2 consecutive runs (shown in sitemap_1 and sitemap_2) shows that a number of wikis with low article count had been removed.
  1. https://community.fandom.com/wiki/Sitemap
  • Fandom includes a sitemap page for search engine optimization purposes. At the time of download, fandom's sitemap was shown to index a few thousand wikis that Special:NewWikis did not index.
  1. https://transfer.archivete.am/12tAP/fandom-wikis-20211116.jsonl.zst
  2. https://transfer.archivete.am/11LzqX/fandom-wikis-update-20220120-ids-2836972to2896300.jsonl.zst
  • There has been ongoing efforts to index all fandom wikis. Data sources 3 and 4 documents various statistics of active fandom wikis at 11/16/2021 and 01/20/2022, with Data Source 4 not including wikis already in 3. However, both data sources are very outdated, with many wiki links being invalid
  1. https://saifmohammad.com/WebPages/NRC-Emotion-Lexicon.htm
  • This data source consists of a list of English words mapped to emotion vectors.

Data Acquisition and Cleaning

Special:NewWikis

https://community.fandom.com/wiki/Special:NewWikis is a repository of all wiki creation events maintained by Fandom. It functions similar to an api, where parameters can be passed to it. The parameters that are relevant here are offset, limit, hub. offset determines the index at which to load wikis, limit denotes the number of wikis to load, and hub determines the wikis with specified genre to load. An arbitrary large number has been set as the beginning offset, and that number is decremented by interval per document download. We first download the relevant markup documents, then parse all \<li> elements to store wiki link, wiki title, and wiki language code. It was observed that there exist many duplicate entries of wiki links. This is likely due to gamepedia's migration to fandom.com, in which many mirror sites on gamepedia were merged with fandom. The data obtained here will used for creating an index of all fandom wikis, so as to evaluate the completeness of the final datasets used.

In[]:
def get_newwikis(start: int, interval: int):
    err = []
    last_link = ''
    ret_links = []
    ret_titles = []
    ret_language_codes = []
    url = 'https://community.fandom.com/wiki/Special:NewWikis'
    header = {
        "User-Agent": "picobrowser/1.0"
    }
    for i in range(start//interval + 1):
        params = {
            "offset": start-i*interval,
            "limit": interval,
        }
        r = requests.get(url, headers=header, params=params)
        print(r.url)
        soup = bs(r.content, "lxml")
        elements: rs = soup.find_all(
            'div', class_='mw-spcontent')[0].find_all('li')
        language_codes = []
        links = []
        titles = []
        for j in elements:
            links.append(j.find('a').get('href'))
            titles.append(j.find('a').getText())
            try:
                language_codes.append(j.getText().strip().split('\n\t\t\t')[1])
            except:
                language_codes.append('--')
                print(f"{j.find('a').get('href')} {j.getText().strip()}")
                err.append((j.find('a').get('href'), j.getText().strip()))
        if len(links) > 0:
            if (links[0] != last_link):
                ret_links.extend(links)
                ret_titles.extend(titles)
                ret_language_codes.extend(language_codes)
                last_link = links[0]
        print(f"Batch: {i} / {start//interval}")
    print(f"language codes {len(ret_language_codes)}")
    print(f"ret_titles {len(ret_titles)}")
    print(f"ret_links {len(ret_links)}")
    ret = pd.DataFrame()
    ret['Wiki'] = ret_titles
    ret['Domain'] = ret_links
    ret['Language Code'] = ret_language_codes
    ret.drop_duplicates(subset=['Domain'], inplace=True)
    return ret
In[]:
data = get_newwikis(3859999, 5000)
#data = get_fandom_wikis(59999, 5000)
data['Domain'] = data['Domain'].str.replace('http://', 'https://')
data.to_csv('data/newwikis.csv', index=False, encoding='utf-16')

Special:NewWikis by Genre

Similarly to above, this time we download with hub passed as an argument, to additionally label wikis by genre. As requesting the endpoint has proved that the highest wiki indexes for each genre are around 30000000, 31000000 has been chosen as a starting point for downloading documents.

In[]:
genres = ['All', 'Humor', 'Gaming', 'Entertainment', 'Wikia', 'Toys', 'Food and Drink', 'Travel', 'Education', 'Lifestyle',
          'Finance', 'Politics', 'Technology', 'Science', 'Philosophy', 'Sports', 'Music', 'Creative', 'Auto', 'Green', 'Wikianswers']
async def get_newwiki(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, params: dict, timeout: int):
    headers = {
        "User-Agent": "picobrowser/1.0"
    }
    try:
        response = await session.get(url=url, headers=headers, params=params, timeout=timeout, ssl=False)
        soup = bs((await response.read()).decode('utf-8'), "lxml")
        language_codes = []
        links = []
        titles = []
        elements: rs = soup.find_all('div', class_='mw-spcontent')[0].find_all('li')
        for j in elements:
            links.append(j.find('a').get('href'))
            titles.append(j.find('a').getText())
            try:
                language_codes.append(j.getText().strip().split('\n\t\t\t')[1])
            except:
                language_codes.append('en')
                print(f"{j.find('a').get('href')} {j.getText().strip()}")
                err.append((j.find('a').get('href'), j.getText().strip()))
        ret = pd.DataFrame([titles, links, language_codes], columns=['Wiki', 'Domain', 'Language Code'])
        return ret
    except:
        print(f"{url}")
        failed.append(url)
        return pd.DataFrame()


async def get_newwiki_batch(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, start: int, interval: int, genre: str, step: int, timeout: int = 5):
    results = await asyncio.gather(*[get_newwiki(session, {
            "offset": start-i*interval,
            "limit": interval,
            "hub": genres.index(genre),
        }, timeout) for i in range(start, start-step*interval, 0-interval)])
    return results


async def get_newwikis_by_genre(start: int, interval: int, genre: str, step: int = 32):
    url = "https://community.fandom.com/wiki/Special:NewWikis"
    connector = aiohttp.TCPConnector(limit=512)
    session = aiohttp.ClientSession(connector=connector)
    data = []
    for i in range(start, 0, -(interval*step)):
        params = {
            "offset": start-i*interval,
            "limit": interval,
            "hub": genres.index(genre),
        }
        stats = await get_newwiki_batch(session, lim_domain_url_map.iloc[i:i+step], timeout=5)
        data.append(stats)
        print(
            f"------------------------------------------------- {i} / {lim_domain_url_map.shape[0]-1}")
    return data

def get_newwikis_by_genre(start: int, interval: int, genre: str):
    err = []
    last_link = ''
    ret_links = []
    ret_titles = []
    ret_language_codes = []
    url = "https://community.fandom.com/wiki/Special:NewWikis"
    header = {
        'User-Agent': 'picobrowser/1.0'
    }
    for i in range(start//interval + 1):
        params = {
            "offset": start-i*interval,
            "limit": interval,
            "hub": genres.index(genre),
        }
        r = requests.get(url, headers=header, params=params)
        print(r.url)
        soup = bs(r.content, "lxml")
        elements: rs = soup.find_all(
            'div', class_='mw-spcontent')[0].find_all('li')
        language_codes = []
        links = []
        titles = []
        for j in elements:
            links.append(j.find('a').get('href'))
            titles.append(j.find('a').getText())
            try:
                language_codes.append(j.getText().strip().split('\n\t\t\t')[1])
            except:
                language_codes.append('--')
                print(f"{j.find('a').get('href')} {j.getText().strip()}")
                err.append((j.find('a').get('href'), j.getText().strip()))
        if len(links) > 0:
            if (links[0] != last_link):
                ret_links.extend(links)
                ret_titles.extend(titles)
                ret_language_codes.extend(language_codes)
                last_link = links[0]
        print(f"Batch: {i} / {start//interval}")
    print(f'language codes {len(ret_language_codes)}')
    print(f'ret_titles {len(ret_titles)}')
    print(f'ret_links {len(ret_links)}')
    ret = pd.DataFrame()
    ret['Wiki'] = ret_titles
    ret['Domain'] = ret_links
    ret['Language Code'] = ret_language_codes
    ret.drop_duplicates(subset=['Domain'], inplace=True)
    return ret
In[]:
entertainment_genres = ['Humor', 'Gaming', 'Entertainment',
                        'Toys', 'Sports', 'Music', 'Creative', 'Travel']

for genre in entertainment_genres:
    get_newwikis_by_genre(3100000, 5000, genre).to_csv(
        f'data/newwikis_{genre.lower()}.csv', index=False, encoding='utf-16')

language codes 592023
ret_titles 592023
ret_links 592023

Sitemap

https://community.fandom.com/wiki/Sitemap is a wiki repository maintained by Fandom, that is primarily used for search engine indexing of wikis. The Sitemap consists of 3 levels, each one hosting subsets of wiki links, with the 3rd level containing wiki language code, genre, wiki name, and wiki link. We traverse the sitemap twice using get_sitemap_level, then run get_sitemap_links on the last level to extract wiki metadata. Sitemap dataset will be the primary index used for downloading wiki metadata and wikitext.

In[]:
async def get_sitemap_links(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, lv3: str, timeout: int):
    html = (await (await session.get(lv3, timeout=timeout, ssl=False)).read()).decode('utf-8')
    df = pd.read_html(html)[0]
    df.insert(0, 'Domain', [i['href'] for i in bs(html, 'lxml').select('.sitemap-showlist a')])
    return df


async def get_sitemap_level(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, lv1: str, base_url: str, timeout: int):
    lv_references = bs((await (await session.get(lv1, timeout=timeout, ssl=False)).read()).decode('utf-8'), "lxml").select(".sitemap-top-level a")
    lv_ret = []
    if len(lv_references) > 0:
        for i in lv_references:
            lv_ret.append(f"{base_url}{i['href']}")
    else:
        print('Error on retriving: ' + lv1)
    return lv_ret
In[]:
session = aiohttp.ClientSession()
lv1 = "https://community.fandom.com/wiki/Sitemap"
base_url = "http://community.fandom.com"
timeout = 9999
lv2 = await get_sitemap_level(session, lv1, base_url, timeout)
lv3 = list(chain.from_iterable(await asyncio.gather(*[get_sitemap_level(session, url, base_url, timeout) for url in lv2])))
sitemap_links = []
print(f'LV2: {len(lv2)}')
lv3_batches = len(lv3)+16
for i in range(0, lv3_batches, 16):
    print(f'LV3: {i}/{lv3_batches-1}')
    sitemap_links.extend(await asyncio.gather(*[get_sitemap_links(session, url, timeout) for url in lv3[i:i+16]]))
sitemap = pd.concat(sitemap_links, axis=0)
sitemap.reset_index(drop=True,inplace=True)
sitemap.rename({'Title': 'Wiki'}, axis=1, inplace=True)
sitemap.rename({'Language': 'Language Code'}, axis=1, inplace=True)
sitemap.rename({'Vertical': 'Genre'}, axis=1, inplace=True)
sitemap['Domain'] = sitemap['Domain'].str.replace('http://', 'https://', regex=False)
sitemap.drop_duplicates(subset=['Domain'], inplace=True)
sitemap.to_csv('data/sitemap.csv', encoding='utf-16', index=False)

LV2: 27
LV3: 0/2651
LV3: 16/2651

Community Archives

Archival efforts has been made to index all fandom wikis in the past. These documents, while mostly outdated, are included so as to cover any wikis not indexed by sitemap and Special:NewWikis. This dataset is primarily used for the overrall index of all fandom wikis, and is not included in the dataset being used.

In[]:
def jsonl_parse(file_name):
    table = pd.read_table(file_name, encoding='utf-8')
    json_tables = []
    for index, item in table.iterrows():
        entry = json.loads(item['json'])
        json_tables.append([entry['url'], entry['lang']])
    df = pd.DataFrame(json_tables, columns=['Domain', 'Language Code'])
    df['Domain'] += '/'
    return df


archive_2021 = jsonl_parse('data/2021_archive.jsonl')
archive_2022 = jsonl_parse('data/2022_archive.jsonl')
archive_2021.to_csv(f'data/archive_2021.csv', index=False, encoding='utf-8')
archive_2022.to_csv(f'data/archive_2022.csv', index=False, encoding='utf-8')

Putting together Wiki Domains

Fandom domains from all datasets are merged to create a comprehensive index of all fandom domains. This will be used for evaluating the completeness of the wiki dataset being downloaded.

Get Wiki Statistics + Remove invalid wiki links

Statistics for each wiki in our domain index are downloaded through Fandom's Mediawiki API. The data is returned in a json format that is then saved as a string in a DataFrame. Additionally, requests that return an error will be counted as invalid wiki links, and are dropped.

In[]:
failed = []


async def get_wiki_statistics(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, url: str, timeout: int):
    headers = {
        "User-Agent": "picobrowser/1.0"
    }
    params = {
        "action": 'query',
        "meta": 'siteinfo',
        "siprop": 'statistics',
        "formatversion": '2',
        "format": 'json',
    }
    try:
        response = await session.get(url=url, headers=headers, params=params, timeout=timeout, ssl=False)
        data = await response.read()
        return [url, data.decode("utf-8")]
    except:
        print(f"{url}")
        failed.append(url)
        return [url, np.nan]


async def get_wiki_statistics_batch(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, domain_url_map: pd.DataFrame, timeout: int = 5):
    results = await asyncio.gather(*[get_wiki_statistics(session, row['Domain'], timeout)
                                     for index, row in domain_url_map.iterrows()])
    return results


async def get_fandom_statistics(domain_url_map: pd.DataFrame, lower: int, upper: int, step: int = 32):
    connector = aiohttp.TCPConnector(limit=512)
    session = aiohttp.ClientSession(connector=connector)
    lim_domain_url_map = domain_url_map[lower:upper+1]
    data = []
    for i in range(0, lim_domain_url_map.shape[0]+step, step):
        stats = await get_wiki_statistics_batch(session, lim_domain_url_map.iloc[i:i+step], timeout=5)
        data.append(stats)
        print(
            f"------------------------------------------------- {i} / {lim_domain_url_map.shape[0]-1}")
    return data
In[]:
links = pd.read_csv('data/domains.csv')
db = await get_fandom_statistics(links, 0, links.shape[0])
links['Statistics'] = db

Parse Statistics to CSV

The statistics above are in a JSON format. We will apply a parser to convert these to a DataFrame

In[]:
def stats_to_csv(x):
    try:
        json_data = json.loads(x['Statistics'])
        return (x['Domain'], json_data['query']['statistics']['batchcomplete'], json_data['query']['statistics']['pages'], json_data['query']['statistics']['articles'],
                json_data['query']['statistics']['edits'], json_data['query']['statistics']['images'], json_data['query']['statistics']['users'],
                json_data['query']['statistics']['activeusers'], json_data['query']['statistics']['admins'], json_data['query']['statistics']['jobs'])
    except:
        return np.nan


parsed_data = links.apply(lambda x: stats_to_csv(x), axis=1)
csv_data = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(
    dict(zip(parsed_data.index, parsed_data.values))).T
csv_data.dropna(inplace=True)
csv_data.columns = ['Domain', 'batchcomplete', 'pages', 'articles',
                    'edits', 'images', 'users', 'activeusers', 'admins', 'jobs']
csv_data.to_csv('data/statistics.csv', encoding='utf-16', index=False)

Labelling newwikis.csv by genre + description

Genre Data collected from Special:NewWikis is combined into 1 dataset, and missing descriptions are filled in with the default Fandom wiki description

In[]:
sitemap_genres = ['Entertainment', 'Games', 'Humor', 'Music', 'Sports', 'Toys', 'Travel']
In[]:
newwikis_entertainment = pd.read_csv('data/newwikis_entertainment.csv', encoding='utf-16')
newwikis_entertainment['Genre'] = 'Entertainment'
newwikis_gaming = pd.read_csv('data/newwikis_gaming.csv', encoding='utf-16')
newwikis_gaming['Genre'] = 'Games'
newwikis_humor = pd.read_csv('data/newwikis_humor.csv', encoding='utf-16')
newwikis_humor['Genre'] = 'Humor'
newwikis_music = pd.read_csv('data/newwikis_music.csv', encoding='utf-16')
newwikis_music['Genre'] = 'Music'
newwikis_sports = pd.read_csv('data/newwikis_sports.csv', encoding='utf-16')
newwikis_sports['Genre'] = 'Sports'
newwikis_toys = pd.read_csv('data/newwikis_toys.csv', encoding='utf-16')
newwikis_toys['Genre'] = 'Toys'
newwikis_travel = pd.read_csv('data/newwikis_travel.csv', encoding='utf-16')
newwikis_travel['Genre'] = 'Travel'

newwikis_fun = pd.concat([newwikis_entertainment, newwikis_gaming, newwikis_humor, newwikis_music, newwikis_sports,
                         newwikis_toys, newwikis_travel]).drop_duplicates(subset=['Domain']).reset_index(drop=True)
newwikis_fun['Description'] = newwikis_fun['Wiki'].copy()
newwikis_fun['Description'] += ' is a community site that anyone can contribute to. Discover, share and add your knowledge!'
newwikis_fun['Domain'] = newwikis_fun['Domain'].str.replace('http://', 'https://')
newwikis_fun
newwikis_fun.to_csv('data/newwikis_fun.csv', index=False, encoding='utf-16')

Combining Sitemap and Special:NewWikis data

Minor parity cleaning is performed on sitemap and Special:NewWikis dataset. The two datasets are then combined, and limited to only english wikis

In[]:
newwikis_fun = pd.read_csv('data/newwikis_fun.csv', encoding='utf-16')
sitemap = pd.read_csv('data/sitemap.csv', encoding='utf-16')
statistics = pd.read_csv('data/statistics.csv', encoding='utf-16')

fandom_wikis_index = newwikis_fun.merge(sitemap, how='outer')
fandom_wikis_index.drop_duplicates(subset=['Domain', 'Genre'], inplace=True)
fandom_wikis_index.to_csv('data/fandom_wikis_index.csv',
                          encoding='utf-16', index=False)
fandom_wikis_index['Domain'] += 'api.php'
fandom_wikis_stats = fandom_wikis_index.merge(
    statistics, how='inner', on='Domain')
fandom_wikis_stats.to_csv('data/fandom_wikis_stats.csv',
                          encoding='utf-16', index=False)

fandom_wikis_stats_en = fandom_wikis_stats.loc[fandom_wikis_stats['Language Code'] == 'en'].reset_index(
    drop=True)
fandom_wikis_stats_en.to_csv(
    'data/fandom_wikis_stats_en.csv', encoding='utf-16', index=False)
In[]:
newwikis_fun = pd.read_csv('data/newwikis_fun.csv', encoding='utf-16')
sitemap = pd.read_csv('data/sitemap.csv', encoding='utf-16')
en_newwikis_fun = newwikis_fun.loc[(newwikis_fun['Language Code']=='en')].reset_index(drop=True)
en_sitemap_fun = sitemap.loc[~(sitemap['Genre']=='Lifestyle') & ~(sitemap['Genre']=='Other') & (sitemap['Language Code']=='en')].reset_index(drop=True)
fandom_wiki_meta_en_fun = en_sitemap_fun.merge(en_newwikis_fun, how='outer').drop_duplicates(subset='Domain').reset_index(drop=True)
fandom_wiki_meta_en_fun.to_csv('data/fandom_wiki_meta_en_fun.csv', encoding='utf-16', index=False)

Removing Duplicate Entries

There exist wikis that have multiple genres, and hence are labelled differently in Fandom's Sitemap and Special:NewWikis. Hence, we apply a join function on these duplicate entries so as to label the wiki with both genres under the same entry.

In[]:
fandom_wikis_stats_en = pd.read_csv('data/fandom_wikis_stats_en.csv', encoding='utf-16')
comb = fandom_wikis_stats_en.drop(columns=['Wiki','Language Code', 'Description', 'batchcomplete', 'pages', 'articles',
    'edits', 'images', 'users', 'activeusers', 'admins', 'jobs']).groupby(['Domain'])['Genre'].apply(', '.join).reset_index()
fandom_wikis_stats_en_stacked_genre = comb.merge(fandom_wikis_stats_en.drop(columns=['Genre']), how='inner', on='Domain').reset_index(drop=True).drop_duplicates(subset=['Domain']).reset_index(drop=True)
In[]:
fandom_wikis_stats_en_stacked_genre.to_csv('data/fandom_wikis_stats_en_stacked_genre.csv', encoding='utf-16', index=False)

Get article index of all wikis

Wikis with an article count from 100-1000 inclusive are downloaded

In[]:
async def get_article_index_entry(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, url: str, limit: int = 500, min_bytes: int = 0, max_bytes: int = 10000000, timeout: int = 10):
    headers = {
        "User-Agent": "picobrowser/1.0"
    }
    apcontinue = ''
    articles = []
    while apcontinue!=None:
        params = {
            'action': 'query',
            'list': 'allpages',
            'aplimit': limit,
            'apminsize': min_bytes,
            'apmaxsize': max_bytes,
            'apcontinue': apcontinue, 
            'formatversion': 2,
            'format': 'json'
        }
        response = await session.get(url=url, headers=headers, params=params, timeout=timeout, ssl=False)
        apcontinue=None
        data = rapidjson.loads((await response.read()).decode("utf-8"))
        articles.extend([(entry['pageid'], entry['title']) for entry in data['query']['allpages']])
        if ('continue' in data):
            apcontinue = data['continue']['apcontinue']
    return [url, articles]


async def get_article_index_batch(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, df: pd.DataFrame, timeout: int = 5):
    results = await asyncio.gather(*[get_article_index_entry(session, row['Domain'], timeout)
                                     for index, row in df.iterrows()])
    return results


async def get_article_index(df: pd.DataFrame, lower: int, upper: int, step: int = 32):
    connector = aiohttp.TCPConnector(limit=512)
    session = aiohttp.ClientSession(connector=connector)
    lim_df = df[lower:upper+1]
    data = []
    for i in range(0, lim_df.shape[0]+step, step):
        stats = await get_article_index_batch(session, lim_df.iloc[i:i+step], timeout=5)
        data.append(stats)
        print(
            f"------------------------------------------------- {i} / {lim_df.shape[0]-1}")
    return data
In[]:
df = pd.read_csv('data/fandom_wiki_stats_en.csv', encoding='utf-16')
nadf = df.loc[(fandom_wiki_stats_en['articles']<=1000) & (fandom_wiki_stats_en['articles']>=100)].reset_index(drop=True)
articles = await get_article_index(nadf, 128)
articles.to_csv('data/article_index_en.csv', index=False)

In[]:
article_index = pd.DataFrame(articles.groupby('Domain', as_index=False), columns = ['Domain', 'Articles']).copy()

Get all articles from each wiki

Wikis with an article count from 100-1000 inclusive are downloaded

In[]:
async def get_article_entry(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, url: str, title:str, timeout: int = 10):
    headers = {
        "User-Agent": "picobrowser/1.0"
    }
    apcontinue = ''
    article_text = ''
    params = {
        'action': 'parse',
        'page': title,
        'prop': 'wikitext', 
        'formatversion': 2,
        'format': 'json'
    }
    response = await session.get(url=url, headers=headers, params=params, timeout=timeout, ssl=False)
    data = rapidjson.loads((await response.read()).decode("utf-8"))
    article_text = data['parse']['wikitext']
    return [url, title, article_text]


async def get_article_batch(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, df: pd.DataFrame, timeout: int = 5):
    results = await asyncio.gather(*[get_article_entry(session, row['Domain'], row['title'], timeout)
                                     for index, row in df.iterrows()])
    return results


async def get_article(df: pd.DataFrame, lower: int, upper: int, step: int = 32):
    connector = aiohttp.TCPConnector(limit=512)
    session = aiohttp.ClientSession(connector=connector)
    lim_df = df[lower:upper+1]
    data = []
    for i in range(0, lim_df.shape[0]+step, step):
        print(i)
        stats = await get_article_batch(session, lim_df.iloc[i:i+step], timeout=5)
        data.extend(stats)
        print(
            f"------------------------------------------------- {i} / {lim_df.shape[0]-1}")
    return data
In[]:
for i in tqdm.tqdm(range(0, article_index.shape[0])):
    article_data = await get_article(article_index.iloc[i, 1], 0, article_index.iloc[i, 1].shape[0], 256)
    article_df = pd.DataFrame(article_data, columns=['Domain', 'Article', 'Markdown'])
    title = article_index.iloc[i, 0].split('.')[0][8:]
    article_df.to_csv(f'data/wikis/wiki_{title}.csv', encoding='utf-8', index=False)

Get edit timestamps of sampled articles
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Fandom Wiki Pages save a timestamp when a user makes an edit. We will be downloading the first 256 timestamps of each Fandom wiki
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
failed = []
async def get_article_edit_timestamps_entry(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, url: str, title:str, limit: int = 256, timeout: int = 5):
    headers = {
        "User-Agent": "picobrowser/1.0"
    }
    params = {
        'action': 'query',
        'prop': 'revisions',
        'titles': title,
        'rvprop': 'timestamp',
        'formatversion': 2,
        'format': 'json',
        'rvlimit': limit
    }
    try:    
        response = await session.get(url=url, headers=headers, params=params, timeout=timeout, ssl=False)
        data = json.loads((await response.read()).decode("utf-8"))
        articles = [entry['timestamp'] for entry in data['query']['pages'][0]['revisions']]
        return [url, title, articles]
    except:
        print(f"{url} {title}")
        return ['', '', []]


async def get_article_edit_timestamps_batch(session: aiohttp.ClientSession, df: pd.DataFrame, timeout: int = 5):
    results = await asyncio.gather(*[get_article_edit_timestamps_entry(session, row['Domain'], row['title'])
                                     for index, row in df.iterrows()])
    return results


async def get_article_edit_timestamps(df: pd.DataFrame, lower: int, upper: int, step: int = 32):
    connector = aiohttp.TCPConnector(limit=512)
    session = aiohttp.ClientSession(connector=connector)
    lim_df = df[lower:upper+1]
    data = []
    for i in range(0, lim_df.shape[0]+step, step):
        stats = await get_article_edit_timestamps_batch(session, lim_df.iloc[i:i+step], timeout=5)
        data.extend(stats)
    return data

To quantify the emotional weightage of a fandom article, the fandom article is tokenised and cleaned, then passed through a mapping that translates each token to it's respective emotional connotation.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Firstly, all wiki csvs in its dedicated folder are listed and sorted.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
wikilist = os.listdir('./data/wikis')
wikilist.sort()
wikilist

Some functions are defined here for error handling and data processing
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
def clean_tokens(x:pd.Series):
    ret = pd.Series(dtype=str)
    if (x.shape[0]>0):
        ret = x.str.replace(pat=r"[^\w]{1,}$",repl='', regex=True).str.replace(pat=r"^[^\w]{1,}",repl='', regex=True).str.lower()
        ret = ret.loc[~ret.str.isnumeric()]
        ret = ret.loc[ret.str.encode('ascii',errors = 'ignore').str.len()==ret.str.len()]
        ret = ret.replace('', np.nan).dropna().reset_index(drop=True)
        return ret
    else:
        return pd.Series(dtype=str)

def get_score(x, k):
    score = emotidict[k].get(x['word'])
    if score!=None:
        return score*x['count']
    else:
        return 0
def bad_wikitext(w):
    try:
        return wtp.parse(str(w)).plain_text().split()
    except:
        return ''
def bad_link(l):
    try:
        return urlparse(l).netloc
    except:
        return 'bad.link'

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
The NRC dataset is read and split into parsed to a list of python dictionaries, with each dictionary being used for 1 emotion, mapping each word to it's corrosponding truth value for that emotion. This is to the reduce time complexity of obtaining emotions from text.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
emotidex = pd.read_csv('data/nrc_word.txt', delimiter='\t')
emotidex_anger = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'anger'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidex_anticipation = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'anticipation'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidex_disgust = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'disgust'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidex_fear = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'fear'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidex_joy = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'joy'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidex_negative = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'negative'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidex_positive = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'positive'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidex_sadness = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'sadness'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidex_surprise = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'surprise'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidex_trust = emotidex.loc[emotidex['emotion'] == 'trust'].loc[:, ['word', 'truth']].set_index('word').to_dict()['truth']
emotidict = [emotidex_anger, emotidex_anticipation, emotidex_disgust, emotidex_fear, emotidex_joy,
             emotidex_negative, emotidex_positive, emotidex_sadness, emotidex_surprise, emotidex_trust]
emotenum = ["anger", "anticipation", "disgust", "fear", "joy", "negative", "positive", "sadness", "surprise", "trust"]
stopwords = open('data/englishST.txt', mode='r').read().split('\n')

Each wiki is read and parsed with WTP to obtain plaintext. Wikis with invalid wikitext formats are dropped. Tokens are generated from plaintext. External links are then found through searching the token lists. A frequency table is generated from the token lists, and each word with given frequency is passed to the NRC dictionary, allowing us to obtain the word emotional truth values with respect to frequency. This data is then saved to sentiment_extlink_checkpt.csv
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
for i in range(18120, len(wikilist)):
    try:
        repo = pd.read_csv(f'data/wikis/{wikilist[i]}')
    except:
        continue
    results = set()
    repo['Markdown'].apply(lambda x: results.update(bad_wikitext(x)))
    tokens = clean_tokens(pd.DataFrame(results, columns=['words'])['words'])
    extlinks = tokens.loc[(tokens.str.contains('https://'))]
    missed_tokens = extlinks.apply(lambda x: x[0:x.find('https://')]).reset_index(drop=True)
    extlinks = extlinks.apply(lambda x: x[x.find('https://'):]).reset_index(drop=True)
    if extlinks.size>0:
        extlink_head = extlinks.apply(lambda x: bad_link(x)).str.split('.').str[-2:].str.join('.').value_counts().head(5).index.to_list()
    else:
        extlink_head = []
    tokens = tokens.loc[~(tokens.str.contains('https://'))]
    final_tokens = pd.concat([tokens, clean_tokens(missed_tokens.replace('', np.nan).dropna().reset_index(drop=True))], axis=0).reset_index(drop=True)
    freq = final_tokens.value_counts()
    newfreq = pd.DataFrame(freq.drop(index=stopwords, errors='ignore')).reset_index().rename({'index': 'word'}, axis=1)
    newfreq.columns = ['word', 'count']
    a = [f"https://{wikilist[i][5:-4]}.fandom.com/api.php", newfreq.head(500)['count'].sum()]
    for j in range(len(emotidict)):
        a.append(newfreq.head(500).apply(lambda x: get_score(x,j), axis=1).dropna().sum())
    a.append(extlink_head)
    print(f'{i} / {len(wikilist)}')
    sentiment_ckpt = pd.concat([sentiment_ckpt,pd.DataFrame([a], columns=["Domain", "wordcount", "anger", "anticipation", "disgust", "fear", "joy", "negative", "positive", "sadness", "surprise", "trust", "ext_links"])])
    if (i%10==0):
        sentiment_ckpt.to_csv('data/sentiment_extlink_checkpt.csv', index=False)

Evaluation of Dataset
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Only a subset of all Fandom Wikis has been taken for answering our questions. Hence, this subset will be evaluated for how much it represents all Fandom Wikis.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
English vs non-English wikis
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Due to constraints imposed by the avaliable emotion lexicon maps, the dataset was limited to english only wikis. A comparison is performed below to show the percentage of data dropped
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
data = pd.read_csv('data/fandom_wikis_stats.csv', encoding='utf-16')['Language Code'].value_counts().reset_index()
lim = data.head(5)
pie_data = pd.concat([lim, pd.DataFrame([['others', data.loc[~data['index'].isin(lim['index'])]['Language Code'].sum()]], columns=['index', 'Language Code'])], axis=0).reset_index(drop=True)

Evaluation of Dataset with article count 100-1000
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
We will further evaluate the subset of data taken from all English wikis. To minimise outliers in wiki size, wikis with 100-1000 articles were chosen for the final dataset. We will first evaluate this subset by comparing it against the overrall English wiki count.

Q1 What are the correlations betweeen emotional weight of wiki text and the positivity/negativity of the same text?
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
First, each wiki will have its wikitext parsed to obtain plaintext using WTP, an open source library for parsing Mediawiki's wikitext format. The resulting plaintext is then cleaned with string manipulation, and tokenized. Each token is then mapped to its relevant emotional weight using the NRC dataset, and summed up with respect to word frequency to obtain the overrall emotional weight of each wiki. each emotional weight is then divided by wordcount to obtain a percentage weightage, and the resulting data is passed to a regression model to obtain an equation representing the correleations between emotional weightage and the wiki's positivity/negativity.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
We will be using the sentiment + external link wiki dataset to answer this question. the external links column is parsed to lists.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
sentiment_extlink_df = pd.read_csv('data/sentiment_extlink_checkpt.csv')
sentiment_extlink_df['ext_links'] = sentiment_extlink_df['ext_links'].apply(ast.literal_eval)
sentiment_extlink_df

24244 rows  10 columns
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
An MLRM to predict positivity is generated as seen below
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
mlm = LinearRegression()
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(maldata[['anger', 'anticipation', 'disgust', 'fear', 'joy', 'sadness', 'surprise', 'trust']], maldata['positive'], test_size=0.2, random_state=0)
mlm.fit(X_train, y_train)
yhat= mlm.predict(X_test)
yhat
plt.figure(figsize=(20,12))
sns.kdeplot(y_test, color='r', label='Actual Value')
sns.kdeplot(yhat,  color='b', label='Fitted Value')

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Out[]:
 
 
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='positive', ylabel='Density'>
 
 
 
 
 
  
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
print(f'yhat={mlm.intercept_} + {mlm.coef_[0]} anger + {mlm.coef_[1]} anticipation + {mlm.coef_[2]} disgust + {mlm.coef_[3]} fear + {mlm.coef_[4]} joy + {mlm.coef_[5]} sadness + {mlm.coef_[6]} surprise + {mlm.coef_[7]} trust')

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
yhat=0.020188826328519566 + 0.18500527911704165 anger + 0.2660235617807205 anticipation + -0.060239690173683025 disgust + 0.1411132471079471 fear + 0.6621365818401261 joy + -0.37150011959429885 sadness + -0.07617231284204737 surprise + 0.687216960987133 trust

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
The fitted equation appears to have little deviation from the actual data. It can be observed from this equation that anger, anticipation and fear have a positive relatively small coefficient, joy and trust have a positive relatively large coefficient. This implies that anger, anticipation, and fear are minor contributors towards positivity, while joy and trust are strong contributors towards positivity. Disgust and Surprise have a negative relatively small coefficient, while sadness has a negative relatively large coefficient. This implies that Disgust and Surprise work against positivity to a small extent, while Sadness decrements positivity the most.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
It is particularly surprising that emotions such as anger and fear contribute towards positivity. Some possible reasons for this could be that terms closely related to anger and fear, can also be phrased in a positive manner. Sadness being the greatest negator of positivity is as expected. However, trust appears to be the greatest contributor towards positivity, as opposed to joy. A likely explanation for this is that Joy can be expressed in a negative light, such as sadism, while Trust is more often a positive emotion.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
An MLRM to predict negativity is generated as seen below
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
mlm2 = LinearRegression()
X_train2, X_test2, y_train2, y_test2 = train_test_split(maldata[['anger', 'anticipation', 'disgust', 'fear', 'joy', 'sadness', 'surprise', 'trust']], maldata['negative'], test_size=0.2, random_state=0)
mlm2.fit(X_train2, y_train2)
yhat2 = mlm2.predict(X_test2)
yhat2
plt.figure(figsize=(20,12))
sns.kdeplot(y_test2, color='r', label='Actual Value')
sns.kdeplot(yhat2,  color='b', label='Fitted Value')

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Out[]:
 
 
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='negative', ylabel='Density'>
 
 
 
 
 
  
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
print(f'yhat={mlm2.intercept_} + {mlm2.coef_[0]} anger + {mlm2.coef_[1]} anticipation + {mlm2.coef_[2]} disgust + {mlm2.coef_[3]} fear + {mlm2.coef_[4]} joy + {mlm2.coef_[5]} sadness + {mlm2.coef_[6]} surprise + {mlm2.coef_[7]} trust')

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
yhat=0.00888615096654366 + 0.47087014369639413 anger + 0.08698425919861141 anticipation + 0.4007340141807568 disgust + 0.34573851313544723 fear + -0.13350281959507235 joy + 0.4721731812740334 sadness + 0.09866755810590114 surprise + -0.01384486918362654 trust

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
The fitted equation appears to have little deviation from the actual data. It can be observed from this equation that anticipation and surprise have a positive relatively small coefficient, and anger, disgust, fear, sadness have a positive relatively large coefficient. This implies that anticipation and surprise are minor contributors towards negativity, while anger, disgust, fear, sadness are strong contributors towards negativity. Trust has a negative relatively small coefficient, while joy has a negative relatively large coefficient. This implies that trust work against negativity to a small extent, while joy decrements negativity the most.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Interestingly, these results do not appear to be the inverse of what is observed for positivity. Hence, we can conclude from this that positivity and negativity are not exact polar opposites of each other in terms of emotions. There appears to be no emotions that greatly work against negativity, with joy having the highest magnitude negative coefficient. of -0.13. This implies that negative text containing phrases that imply posivitity, will remain largely negative.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
As an extension to this question, An MLRM to predict anger is generated as seen below
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
mlm3 = LinearRegression()
X_train3, X_test3, y_train3, y_test3 = train_test_split(maldata[['anticipation', 'disgust', 'fear', 'joy', 'sadness', 'surprise', 'trust']], maldata['anger'], test_size=0.2, random_state=0)
mlm3.fit(X_train3, y_train3)
yhat3 = mlm3.predict(X_test3)
yhat3
plt.figure(figsize=(20,12))
sns.kdeplot(y_test3, color='r', label='Actual Value')
sns.kdeplot(yhat3,  color='b', label='Fitted Value')

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Out[]:
 
 
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='anger', ylabel='Density'>
 
 
 
 
 
  
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
print(f'yhat={mlm3.intercept_} + {mlm3.coef_[0]} anticipation + {mlm3.coef_[1]} disgust + {mlm3.coef_[2]} fear + {mlm3.coef_[3]} joy + {mlm3.coef_[4]} sadness + {mlm3.coef_[5]} surprise + {mlm3.coef_[6]} trust')

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
yhat=0.0011258610623556403 + -0.07092094435737664 anticipation + 0.15268724920672172 disgust + 0.6021373447985878 fear + -0.044040220722326884 joy + 0.06293033823567395 sadness + 0.2484674537708601 surprise + 0.0007937735974912763 trust

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
The fitted equation appears to have little deviation from the actual data. It can be observed from this equation that sadness and trust have a positive relatively small coefficient, and disgust, fear, surprise have a positive relatively large coefficient. This implies that sadness and trust are minor contributors towards anger, while disgust, fear, surprise are strong contributors towards anger. anticipation and joy have a negative relatively small coefficient. This implies that anticipation and joy work against anger to a small extent.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
There appears to be no major contributor towards decrementing anger. This implies that text that indicates anger will not decrease its emotional vector significantly with the addition of other words that indicate other emotions.

Miscellaneous links appear to greatly outnumber the top 10 links. discord.gg links appear to be used to a significant volume by most genres of wikis, with the exception being Sports and Travel wikis. Considering discussion of these genres rarely takes place on discord servers, this is to be expected. Facebook appears to be favoured significantly by Sports and Travel Wikis, while being used the least in Anime Wikis. Considering the average age of Facebook's userbase is higher than most platforms, it makes sense that these two genres, which are typically dominated by an older fanbase, reference Facebook a significant amount. Fandom.com links are commonly referenced by all wikis, with the exception of Sports and Travel wikis. This implies that Sports are Travel wikis are largely self contained, not requiring references to each other. Google.com is most commonly referenced by Sports Wikis. Roblox.com appears to be rarely used, only being used the most in Games, Movies, Music, and TV wikis. Twitter.com is most favoured by Anime wikis, and by Music, Entertainment, Comics and TV wikis to a smaller extent. This is likely due to the large diversity in Twitter content. Wikia.com is referenced very little by Fandom wikis, and is not referenced by Sports and Travel wikis. Wikia's domain was the original domain name for fandom, and it is surprising that it prevelant at all, given that Fandom has migrated most wikis to the new domain. This implies that there are a significant number of dated wikis that still reference fandom's old domain. Wikipedia.org is referenced the most by Books Wikis. This implies that books are often documented by Wikipedia, which is true. Youtube's link shortener is most commonly used by Toys wikis, and its full domain is most commonly used by Humor wikis. This is likely due to Youtube being a platform that hosts a large volume of "meme" media.

It can be seen that archive.org and co.uk are highly favoured by Travel Wikis. It is possible that Travel wikis use archive.org as a permenant storage method for Tourism sites. Deviantart is used the most by Books and Comics wikis. As Deviantart is an art blogging platform, this is of no surprise. Games Wikis appear to use discord.gg links the most, with other wikis using discord.gg little, if at all. This is again expected, considering the great number of discord servers related to games that exist. Similarly to the previous heatmap. Facebook appears to be favoured significantly by Sports and Travel Wikis, while being used the least in Anime Wikis. It is also possible that Facebook profiles of sports players are being referenced in these wikis, leading to the high frequency. Fandom.com links are most referenced by Books and Toys wikis. external fandom.com links are often links to other fandom wikis. Hence, we can infer from this that Toy and Books wikis are highly connected with each other. Google.com is most commonly referenced by Sports and Games Wikis. Instagram appears to be most favoured by Music wikis. This makes sense due to the presence of many music artists on Instagram. nocookie.net appears to be the most favoured by Toys wikis. nocookie.net is used by fandom wikis to prevent site cookies from being sent to Fandom servers, hence reducing request size. It is surprising that Toys Genre appears to favour using nocookie.net, as opposed to there being no visible outlier. Reddit appears to be used the most by Games wikis. Similarly to discord, Reddit is often used for discussion of games, so this is again of no surprise. Soundcloud is used the most by Music wikis, which is expected considering Soundcloud is a platform for hosting music. Twitter.com is most favoured by Anime wikis, and by Music, Entertainment, Comics and TV wikis to a smaller extent. Twitter hosts a large variety of content, so it is surprising that Anime appears to be highly prevelant on Twitter. Wikipedia.org is referenced the most by Books Wikis. Youtube's link shortener is most commonly used by Toys wikis, and its full domain is most commonly used by Humor wikis. This is likely due to Youtube being a platform that hosts a large volume of "meme" media. It can be observed that Toys wikis appear to employ "safety nets", with the nocookie request and link shortener. This could be a side effect of trying to appeal to a smaller audience.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Q3 How has the presence of movies on Fandom changed over time?
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
First, the timestamps from all Movie wikis are collected into 1 Dataframe, and passed to a KDE plot. Then, each wiki's timestamps will be overlayed using KDE plots.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Timestamps from each wiki article are read into a Dataframe of Series of Timestamps.

Out[182]:

Similarly to the KDE graph, the density of wiki edits appears to increase. However, it can be noted from this graph that there are a significant number of sharp spikes in wiki activity. This implies that a significant number of Movie wikis experience a number of edits within a short space of time. This would make sense, as Movies rarely change past their release, hence requiring edits to be made only on movie release.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Conclusion
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
We can conclude that Fandom's wikitext emotional weightage correlations with positivity/negativity follows what would be expected, with emotions traditionally associated with positivity being represented as such in the regression equation, and vice versa. However, positivity and negativity in text are not polar opposites, and a text's emotions can be interpreted differently based on context, allowing for normally positivt words to also have negative connotations
 
External Domains also appear to follow expectations, with sites that are closely related to specific genres, being the most referenced by that wiki genre. We can also conclude that there are popular domains such as Soundcloud that are rarely the most used external link in the wiki, but are still present in many wikis. We have also found that sites that typically host diverse content such as Twitter, may be referenced by Fandom sites of specific genres more than others.
 
Movies have been gaining a larger presence in Fandom over time, but it is worth noting that many of such wikis only experience activity for a short period of time after a movie is released.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Recommendations or Further Works
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
I would recommend sites such as Twitter and Youtube to capitalize on the high frequency of their domain being used in Fandom. Fandom could obtain permission from Twitter and Youtube to allow custom embeds in Fandom wikis.
 
I am looking to expanding the wiki dataset scope of this project in the future, so as to have a larger timestamp dataset for Q3. I would also like to look into the use of Natural Language Processing for developing an AI model with my dataset.

def clean_tokens(x:pd.Series):
    ret = pd.Series(dtype=str)
    ret = x.str.replace(pat=r"[^\w]{1,}$",repl='', regex=True).str.replace(pat=r"^[^\w]{1,}",repl='', regex=True).str.lower()
    ret = ret.loc[~ret.str.isnumeric()]
    ret = ret.loc[ret.str.encode('ascii',errors = 'ignore').str.len()==ret.str.len()]
    ret = ret.replace('', np.nan).dropna().reset_index(drop=True)
    return ret
results = set()
utwikirepo['Markdown'].apply(lambda x: results.update(wtp.parse(str(x)).plain_text().split()))
tokens = clean_tokens(pd.DataFrame(results, columns=['words'])['words'])

In[]:
 
 
 
def get_score(x):
    score = emotidict[i].get(x['word'])
    if score!=None:
        return score*x['words']
    else:
        return 0

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
In[]:
 
 
 
freq = final_tokens.value_counts()
newfreq = pd.DataFrame(freq.drop(index=stopwords, errors='ignore')).reset_index().rename({'index': 'word'}, axis=1)
a = []
for i in range(len(emotidict)):
    a.append(newfreq.head(500).apply(lambda x: get_score(x), axis=1).dropna().sum())
f5 = pd.DataFrame(a, columns=['freq'])
f5['emote'] = emotenum

In[]:
 
 
 
time_series = pd.Series(dtype=float)
for i in range(0,timestamp_repo.shape[0]):
    time_series = pd.concat([time_series, pd.Series(json.loads(timestamp_repo.iloc[i]['Timestamp'].replace('\'', '"'))).apply(lambda x: pd.Timestamp(x))])
time_series.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
